fields.description: * The location data needs to be mapped to our route ‚Üí our route is represented by 1000s of (lat, long) points that connect to represent a route. The location data from the car will not exactly match the location points of our route so we need to figure out which of our route‚Äôs location point the car is nearest to (because this will be where the car is ‚Äúat‚Äù in our route). A problem that we have is that the route may cross over itself and we don‚Äôt know which direction it‚Äôs going (as that is needed for other microservices). One option is to use the sliding window technique but the problem is that the route is 1000s of points and the microservice is stateless. We need to figure out an algorithm for this (or design the service in another way)

We want to calculate the *angle* at which the rays are hitting the flat cells over a period of time. This will then translate into the intensity of the suns rays which will allow for deciphering of how much energy the car is receiving.

As a next step, we want to measure total energy changes over time interval and different locations.

# Make the lat, long, and time changes dynamic - can we set lat, long, and times and receive the same simulation results?

As an MVP, let‚Äôs focus on the ‚Äúdirectness‚Äù angle of the solar rays to the car‚Äôs arrays. Assume the solar arrays are laid out flat in the car.

# Angle of Approach for a Fixed Lat Long over a set time-interval

fields.summary: Write Program To Calculate Benefit Cost Score
fields.description:
Given the following information:

* Cumulative Distance(Miles)
* Major turns
* Number of stops
* Level 1 Turns (Easy)
* Level 2 turns (Medium)
* Level 3 Turns (Hard)
* Average Speed
* Estimated Completion Time
* Current Status

Write a program to calculate the benefit cost score based on the details mentioned in the benefit cost score page.

Experiment with different weights for the data and methods if possible to determine the best possible formula. This can go in the confluence!

*Suggested Formula:* 
Loss = Time + (Weighted average of turns) + Number of stops
Use softmax to get the value for loss between 0 and 1.
Then find score = Distance/Softmax(Loss)

*Resources*

[Benefit Cost Score Page|https://uwmidsun.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/S/pages/3144581153/Benefit+Cost+Score]

[The routebook|https://www.americansolarchallenge.org/ASC/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ASC-2021-Route-Book.pdf]

*Steps*

# Write a function to calculate the cost benefit score.
# Use pytest to test the code.
# Document the formula used to process the inputs (and why).
# Push to github in branch for review.
